THE ROAD TO IVARSTEAD — RUNSHEET (Fire B, the journey)  [DRAFT — working content; RTF-build later]
=====================================================================
SCOPE: Riften gates -> the foot of the 7,000 Steps. ROAD ONLY (the town is the next segment).
THE SPINE: a quiet leg doing three jobs — (1) re-introduce ESBERN (comedy + strategy),
  (2) give the table a BREATH (respite + personal threads), (3) teach that the DRAGONS OWN THE
  SKY (the hide). Normal physics the whole way; the first faint time-wrongness only at the end.
ROSTER ON THE MOVE: Davinia (ISMARA fronting — silver skin), Saijah (carrying ALFONSO, the
  rapier), Orion. Cart: Bjorn, Mila, ESBERN (hidden in the false bottom), Nora, GEAR, Ylva,
  Varon. Animals: MABLE (old, dragon-shaken) + the BLACK MARE (new, fearless warhorse).
  NOTE: Krusp & Danica are GONE to Windhelm — NOT on this journey. Kyboh is gone (believed dead).

=====================================================================
GM RULES BLOCK — "TWO SHADOWS" (the dragon hide)
=====================================================================
The hide is the set-piece. It is NOT a fight — two Krosulhah-tier dragons on open ground is a
TPK, and the whole point is to teach that hiding is the only play. Run it as a NOTICE CLOCK, d20.

ONE STORM DRAGON, ONE FIRE DRAGON. They hunt by different senses. A party that understands the
  difference can play them against each other. A party that doesn't will feed both at once.
  STORM DRAGON: hunts by air pressure, ground vibration, and electrical resonance. Detects
    movement (wheels, hooves), magical activity (tonal hum, aura-work), and the dead-zone
    pressure of something hiding. Overhead signature: sharp clean-edged shadow, geometric banking
    turns, air cracks almost-audibly when it climbs. Wingbeats precise and staccato. Smells of
    ozone and nothing alive.
  FIRE DRAGON: hunts by heat signature and scent. Detects body heat, metabolic odor (blood,
    breath, fear-sweat, rot), and thermal plumes from any warm surface. Overhead signature:
    wavy, shimmering shadow (heat-distortion wraps it), lazy muscular glide on thermals.
    Wingbeats deep and slow. Smells of sulfur and charred stone. The air ahead of it warms.
  THE CORE TENSION: silence and stillness mask the storm dragon. Cold and scent-suppression
    mask the fire dragon. The party cannot do both at once without cost.

THE NOTICE TRACK: 6 boxes, starts empty. The two dragons hunt/feed overhead; they are NOT
  scripted to engage. They tick toward awareness on the party's OWN mistakes.

THE BEATS: the crossing plays as 5 COMPLICATION BEATS. Each beat the GM frames a thing that
  threatens to give them away — almost always one of the party's OWN ASSETS. The responsible
  character rolls d20 + relevant skill vs an escalating difficulty (FROGS ladder: Easy +2 /
  Moderate 0 / Hard -2 / Very Hard -6), SUCCESS on 11+ after the modifier.
   - Success: tell contained. No Notice.
   - Failure: Notice +1.
   - Fumble (nat 1): Notice +2; a dragon banks toward them (next beat one step harder).
   - Crit (nat 20): they actively mask — Notice -1 (min 0); next beat one step easier.

DIFFICULTY CLIMBS as they circle nearer: Beat 1 Easy(+2) -> Beat 2 Moderate(0) ->
  Beat 3 Hard(-2) -> Beat 4 Hard(-2) -> Beat 5 Very Hard(-6).

PROACTIVE PLAY IS REWARDED — every smart move drops the next beat one step (or grants
  advantage): kill the lanterns, douse the cookfire, still the cart, let Orion (no heartbeat,
  no breath) scout ahead, have Ismara sheathe the cart's heat in cold, power GEAR down. Say YES
  to cleverness.

FAIL STATE: Notice hits 6 -> the cart is spotted -> the dragons dive. TELEGRAPH the
  unwinnability relentlessly BEFORE this (the shadow blots the sun, the heat of a charging
  throat) so the table runs/scatters rather than rolling initiative. If they fight anyway it is
  a TPK and you warned them. (This is the teeth that keep the hide honest.)

THE TELLS (5 complications, each tied to an asset and one dragon type):
  BEAT 1 — MABLE SPOOKS [FIRE DRAGON] (charred brimstone on the wing-wind hits the old mare
    before anything else does — predator-scent in the thermals). Bjorn rolls (animal-handling/
    Agility). The BLACK MARE in harness beside her = one step EASIER (the fearless horse steadies
    the frightened one — the purchase paying off). Hot wind. The new mare's nostrils flare first.
  BEAT 2 — GEAR HUMS [STORM DRAGON] (amber lamp + tonal whine = atmospheric resonance; the
    pressure-hunter hears the air singing around it). Saijah/Orion (Guile). GEAR needs PERMISSION
    to power down (callback to the Cognitorium threshold) — a quick beat. Killing the hum masks
    from the storm dragon; it does nothing for the fire dragon.
  BEAT 3 — ALFONSO'S ROT-AURA [FIRE DRAGON] (rot = metabolic decay = heat-signature + scent
    plume drifting downwind; a fire dragon's nose is extraordinary). Saijah (bearer). Alfonso
    pulls the aura tight through the bearer-link — auto-success if she lets him drive the hand.
  BEAT 4 — A SMALL HUMAN SOUND [STORM DRAGON] (Mila's frightened breath, a wet cough — a
    vibration-spike in the pressure field; the pressure-hunter hears discontinuity in the
    silence). Bjorn or Saijah — comfort, not a stat; steadying Mila IS the roll. Tender beat.
  BEAT 5 — HEAT BLOOM [FIRE DRAGON] (the cart's warmth glows to a diving eye; frost turns
    slick water underneath the frame). Davinia/Ismara. Ismara can sheathe it in cold (Aegis
    turned inward) — BUT using the gift TICKS THE CDI; a quiet temptation. The cart cannot be
    silenced AND iced at once without burning both actions — choose.

THE WORST MOMENT (Beat 5, or on any failure that puts the dragons lowest): the danger reaches
  MILA — Bjorn's flare (Scene 6).

=====================================================================
SCENE 1 — THE OPEN ROAD (and the man in the floor)
=====================================================================
[Set this once Riften is well behind them — lake out of sight, road climbing into open country.]

READ ALOUD: "The gates of Riften fall behind you and the road climbs into autumn — gold hills,
clean cold air, the cart finding its rhythm on dry stones. There is space out here. Room to
breathe. The Rift opens wide around you, all amber and pine, and the quiet after a city is its
own kind of medicine. Mable plods, steady as old faith. The black mare walks beside her, head
up, ears easy, reading the world and finding nothing in it to fear. And from somewhere under
the cart's floorboards, muffled by canvas and the false bottom, a dry old voice says, with
enormous dignity: '...Are we far enough now? My legs have fallen asleep.'"

THE BEAT (COMEDY): nobody has thought about Esbern since Riften. Let it land — a pause, then the
slow dawning. Play it for the laugh.

ESBERN (climbing out, stiff, blinking at the open sky):
  "You forgot me. The last Blade. The only living loremaster who can read Alduin's Wall — and I
  have been lying in a false floor for two days because not one of you remembered I was down
  there." (beat) "Magnificent. Truly. The fate of the world is in remarkable hands."

WHY HE WAS DOWN THERE (deliver in play, not a lecture): if asked —
  "The Thalmor have a standing warrant on me, and Riften is crawling
  with their eyes. I could not be seen within those walls. Out here?" (squints at the empty
  hills) "Out here I am just an old man on a cart. Now — where are we going, and what fresh end
  of the world am I to help you with?"

=====================================================================
SCENE 2 — ESBERN EARNS HIS KEEP
=====================================================================
The strategic briefing — but NEVER a wall of lore. Give him a MAP and let the party pull it out
of him by asking. He answers in pieces, plain, reacting to what THEY know. He unfolds it
against the side of the cart: a conspiracy web. Forty years of obsessive work on a large hide
base, pinned over with torn parchment scraps, connected by four colors of string:
  RED = confirmed resurrections (Sahloknir, Krosulhah — he keeps LOOKING at those two nodes)
  BLACK = suspected burial sites dotted across Skyrim in a cramped, decades-old hand
  GREEN = cult infrastructure (ritual sites, safehouses, the Eldergleam, the Throat undercroft)
  GOLD = artifacts — radiating outward from one central blank node he won't stop touching
THE HOOK: the blank node is Bleak Falls Barrow. The Dragonstone. The missing translation key
that would make every other string on the web mean something. He hates that blank more than
anything he has hated in forty years of paranoid scholarship.

- ON THE TWO APOCALYPSES (if they describe the black sap / the cult): "Two different ends,
  walking toward us from two directions. The dragons want to rule a dead world. These
  root-rotters — Dagon's people — they don't want to rule anything. They want there to be
  nothing left to rule. Don't confuse them. The dragons are a war. The other thing is an
  unmaking."
- ON WHERE THEY'RE GOING: "The Throat of the World is not just the dragons' holy mountain. It is
  a PILLAR — one of the stones that holds the floor of the world up. If the cult cracks it, time
  itself runs in the cellar. That's what your archer feels."
- THE THING HE ACTUALLY WANTS (the recurring pressure): taps a blank spot on the map. "Bleak
  Falls Barrow. There is a stone in it — the Dragonstone — a map of every dragon grave in
  Skyrim. Without it, we wait for each dragon to find US. With it, we find THEM first. Everything
  we do until we have that stone is a flinch, not a plan." -> Plant it. Don't resolve it. He'll
  say it again, and again, the whole campaign.

GM NOTE: Esbern is the lore-dump risk incarnate. NEVER let him monologue uninterrupted. Cut him
off with a complication, a question, a beat of Ylva groaning. The clue is in the conversation,
never in the dump.

=====================================================================
SCENE 3 — THE RESPITE (the Khajiit caravan)
=====================================================================
A deliberate breath. Warmth, color, the world being alive. NO threat.

READ ALOUD: "The smell hits before the sight — cardamom and cumin and woodsmoke and something
sweeter under it, faintly foreign. Then the light: lanterns strung between tent poles, half a
dozen canvas pavilions in rust and saffron and deep blue arranged in a loose crescent off the
verge, brass braziers burning at the edges for warmth and spectacle both. Bolts of dyed fabric
hang on lines between the poles. Somewhere inside a hand-drum beats. This is the Khajiit camp —
not a caravan moving through but a small city that springs up in the margin between 'inside the
walls' and 'on the road,' because the walls have never opened for them. A woman in a coat of a
hundred patches steps out from the largest tent and spreads her arms wide. 'Ah — travelers! Good
ones, this one can tell. The road is kinder with company. Come — Ahkari has tea, has trinkets,
has STORIES, and the stories are free because no one ever buys them anyway.'"

AHKARI (caravan mistress) — warm, shrewd, a fence and a gossip. Use her for three things:

(1) TRADE. Stock is thinner than she'd like — disrupted caravans, inflated road costs; she's
    nervous but hiding it under hospitality. She buys surplus from the party at good prices
    (she needs to restock). She sells:
    ALCHEMY (Alfonso / Ismara's cure thread): moonflower petals (silvery, cold to touch),
      nightshade in suspension jars, powdered moonstone, luminous cave-fungi. Rare. She knows
      exactly what she has and prices accordingly.
    RANGING (Saijah): non-standard fletched arrows (heartwood — lighter, keener flight), dried
      reagents for camp-alchemy (spider silk, moon salt, powdered bone for poisons), a rolled
      huntsman map of old Khajiit caravan routes through the Rift.
    GENERAL: spiced travel-bread that keeps for weeks, dried fruit, waterskins, rope, small
      enchanted curios labeled in Khajiit script nobody in the party can read.
    Haggling is social, not a fight. Fair prices as a rule — but she needs to restock and will
    go lower on bulk trades than she'd normally consider.

(2) RUMORS (roll d20 or pick — feed the campaign):
   1-5   "Ivarstead is emptying. Half the village ran. The other half is too poor or too
          stubborn — and something's wrong with the TIME up the steps. A pilgrim walked three
          days and came down having aged a week."
   6-10  "Windhelm sealed its gates. Plague. They say the Stormcloak army is rotting from the
          inside — and that two strangers, a grim swordsman and a coughing priestess, walked IN
          when everyone sane was walking out." [Krusp & Danica — Fire A, heard as rumor.]
   11-15 "Black-Briar's looking for someone. Quiet-like. Ahkari does not ask who; Ahkari likes
          her throat where it is." [Seeds the DIRGE thread without naming it.]
   16-19 "The sky's been WRONG east of here. A hunter swore he saw a dragon — a real one, not a
          story. Two of them. Going toward the Rift." [The scouts — third-hand; the party
          cannot know the target.]
   20    "You've a sword that watches people. No — don't show Ahkari. Some things this one is
          happier not knowing." [She's noticed Alfonso. Unsettling. Let it sit.]

(3) A SMALL HUMAN MOMENT. Ahkari's people have a child too — and Mila, who has spent her whole
    life learning to be invisible, watches the caravan kids play with the careful hunger of a
    girl who has never been allowed to. Let Bjorn notice. The warm thing in the chapter.

=====================================================================
SCENE 4 — DOWNTIME & CONNECTION (camp, the night before the open stretch)
=====================================================================
The camp is a mile off the road, sheltered against a low embankment. Fire going. No walls, no
city, no Thalmor. The closest thing to ease this group has had in weeks. Let it breathe.

Run as sequential vignettes. GM sets the situation and plays the NPCs. Players drive entirely.
RULE: never write a player's line or decision — only the situation they walk into.

---------------------------------------------------------------------
VIGNETTE 1 — ISMARA'S WORK (early evening, by the fire)
---------------------------------------------------------------------
THE SITUATION: Ismara (Davinia's player at the wheel) settles near the fire with the Forelhost
  Codex open across her knees. She wants the rapier within arm's reach. She has a specific
  observation about the interaction between Alfonso's rot-frequency and the engineered strain —
  something she noticed in the Codex, something she needs confirmed or challenged.

AIM FOR ISMARA: She is warm here. Genuinely useful, genuinely engaged. She is not running a
  manipulation — she believes in the work, and that is exactly what makes this dangerous. The
  Davinia player should enjoy wielding her intelligence freely. CDI does NOT tick here. This is
  the honey, not the sting.

THE OPENING: She brings a specific technical question to the rapier's bearer. She opens the
  floor. What happens next belongs to the players.

BEAT — IF THE THREAD ENGAGES: the cure-work advances. Ismara is satisfied. Something in her
  settles, briefly, into something almost human. The Davinia player should feel the warmth of
  it — that is the trap working as designed.
BEAT — IF IT DOESN'T: Ismara closes the Codex, notes the absence without comment, and rises.
  Either way — Ylva has been watching from across the fire the entire time. See Vignette 3.

---------------------------------------------------------------------
VIGNETTE 2 — NORA + GEAR (early evening, edge of firelight)
---------------------------------------------------------------------
THE SITUATION: Nora is at the periphery of camp with GEAR, her research notes spread on a flat
  stone. She has been asking GEAR questions every night for a week. GEAR answers everything with
  complete technical precision and no filter whatsoever.

TONIGHT she is asking about phylacteries — specifically whether a soul anchored in an object
  can be copied rather than simply transferred. GEAR is explaining, in accurate tonal terms,
  exactly the mechanism Hjolmar used. He does not know this is dangerous. He is simply answering.

The rapier is across the fire. Nora's eyes go to it twice during the conversation.

GM NOTE: Every session Nora spends with GEAR she understands more about what Alfonso IS — and
  what that knowledge could build toward. The party can intervene if they notice what she's
  asking. If no one does, GEAR will finish the answer and Nora will write it down.

BEAT: Does anyone notice? Does anyone intervene? She knows more by the end of this than she did
  at the start, regardless.

---------------------------------------------------------------------
VIGNETTE 3 — YLVA (mid-evening; fires after Vignette 1)
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Ylva does not brood. She acts.

THE SITUATION: The moment Ismara rises from the cure-work — Ylva stands up. She crosses the
  fire. She puts herself directly in Ismara's path. She does not have words for what she is
  feeling; she doesn't reach for them. Instead she challenges: a sparring match, an arm-wrestle,
  something immediate and physical. This is how Ylva resolves confusion. She wants contact with
  the silver woman. She doesn't know yet if she wants to fight her or hold her. It doesn't matter.
  She is in front of her now, and she is waiting.

ISMARA'S CHOICE (player-driven): The silver woman can engage, deflect with cool precision, or
  simply walk past. All three land differently on Ylva. Ismara looking at her with Davinia's eyes
  and Ismara's detachment is its own specific cruelty — Ylva will feel whatever she gets.

BEAT: Ylva walks away with something she didn't have before. She doesn't get what she wants.
  She sits back down, sharpens her axe, and doesn't look at anyone for the rest of the evening.

---------------------------------------------------------------------
VIGNETTE 4 — NORA & ORION → THE RECKONING (late evening; fire burned low)
---------------------------------------------------------------------
THE SITUATION: Nora finds Orion where he has settled apart from the others. She doesn't ask.
  She sits down next to him — close. This has been building for a long time. Tonight she decides.

WHAT SHE BRINGS: not performance, not strategy — earnestness. She is 18 and she means it
  completely. She tells him something true: why she is here, what she wants from him specifically.
  She makes herself available. The choice belongs to Orion.

IF ORION DOES NOT ENGAGE: she accepts it without drama. She says goodnight and goes to her
  bedroll. The door stays open. Nothing is destroyed.

IF ORION ENGAGES — they sleep together. And then, immediately:

  THE RING goes from cold to KILLING cold.

  Orion cannot move. Not paralyzed — HELD. The Ring's grip is total. Valerius is simply present,
  a sending, unhurried, taking up no space he doesn't intend.

  VALERIUS: "You served me well. For a long time. I want you to understand — that is not nothing."
  (a beat, genuine)
  "But you are a hand. And a hand that will not close when I will it..."
  He takes the off-hand. Below the elbow. Clean. No cruelty in the motion — only efficiency.
  "...is trimmed. Serve better."

  MECH (PERMANENT): Any minor action requiring the off-hand is now a major action until Orion
  acquires a prosthetic. No saving throw. No mitigation. This is months of disobedience landing
  at once, and the warmth he just took is the reason it happened tonight and not earlier.

  NORA is present. She sees all of it.

GM: Do not soften this. The beat with Nora exists so that Valerius has something to threaten
  beyond Orion's body. He now knows about her.

---------------------------------------------------------------------
VIGNETTE 5 — SAIJAH (late evening, after camp quiets)
---------------------------------------------------------------------
THE SITUATION: Saijah is awake when most of the fire has gone to coals. The migraine — which
  Alfonso's rot-frequency had been dampening without anyone quite realising it, a side effect of
  his aura quieting Kynareth's signal — is coming back. Not the full assault. Not yet. A low
  directional ache, pointing south. Toward the mountains. She knows what this means. Tomorrow
  will be different.

VARON makes himself known. He does not approach the fire — he steps into the light just far
  enough to be visible, across the camp. He meets her eyes. He gestures: small, no pressure.
  Come talk, or don't. He'll be over there.

  IF SAIJAH COMES: he apologizes. Plainly, without excuse. He fled her at the moment she needed
  steadiness and he knows the cost of that. He does not ask forgiveness. He offers presence.
  IF SAIJAH DOESN'T COME: in the morning there is something left near her bedroll — a small
  carved piece, made overnight. An apology in object form. He will not try to speak to her again
  unless she comes to him first. He means this.

BEAT: The migraine's return is the last quiet night she will have for a long time. She can spend
  it alone or with someone who at least knows what he did wrong. Both are valid. Neither fixes
  what's coming.

---------------------------------------------------------------------
VIGNETTE 6 — BJORN & MILA (late evening, at the cart)
---------------------------------------------------------------------
THE SITUATION: Mila cannot sleep. She is sitting up on the cart, blanket around her shoulders,
  watching the coals. Bjorn is there — he is always there when she is awake late. He has been
  keeping a careful distance since she asked him why he felt like more than one person. Tonight
  he closes it.

He sits down next to her. He lets the silence be what it is.

Then he tells her something true — not about himself, not the dragon souls or the War-Hound or
  the sisters. Something smaller and more honest: what a promise actually weighs. That he has
  made them before and broken one and carried it for forty years. That he is not going to let
  that happen again.

He does not dress it up. He says it plain, in the voice he uses for the things that matter.
  Then he gets up and shows her: left side of the horse, breathing even, hands open. The black
  mare — proud, unbothered by almost everything — suffers the careful child where she suffers
  nobody else.

BEAT: Mila brushes the mare. Somewhere in the middle of it her hands stop shaking. Bjorn
  watches her face and does not let her see him watching.

=====================================================================
SCENE 5 — THE SHADOW ON THE SNOW (THE HIDE)
=====================================================================
The open stretch — a high, treeless saddle, the cart fully exposed, nowhere to go. Mid-day.
Then the light changes.

GM TERRAIN BRIEF (establish this before or as the threat arrives — players will use it to plan):
  The saddle is roughly 400 meters of bare pale stone and snow-dusted ground, road running
  straight across. The sky is enormous up here. What the party has to work with:
    LOW SCREE BANKS (2-3 feet of loose rock flanking the road — concealment if prone, not cover)
    SHALLOW DRAINAGE CUTS off the road's edge (barely wide enough for a person lying flat)
    THE CART (the largest and most visible profile on the saddle by far)
    THE HORSES (add significantly to the thermal and acoustic signature)
  What they do NOT have: trees, walls, boulders, structures, any fold in the ground deep enough
  to drop behind. The saddle is functionally naked. Going still and cold and silent is the only
  play. Running makes them bigger targets. Fighting is death.

READ ALOUD: "The road tops the rise and the world becomes sky. No trees. No walls. Nothing
between you and the open cold but four hundred meters of bare pale stone, and the cart is the
only dark thing on it. You are halfway across when the temperature drops and the air smells
wrong — sulfur and ozone together, two different wrongnesses layered — and then the first shadow
sweeps the snow. Sharp-edged, geometric, fast. A second crosses it immediately after, this one
rippling at the edges like heat off a forge in summer. And then the sound: a double heartbeat
in the air above you — a precise tearing crack of wings and under it a deep, slow muscular
THRUM — and you know that sound. You have heard it twice. You nearly died both times.
   There are two of them up there. Wheeling. Hunting. The snow glows white beneath you like a
lantern held up to the dark.
   They have not seen you yet.
   You have a cart. Two horses. A child. An old man. And four hundred meters of open ground with
nowhere to go and no world where you win a fight."

FRAME THE STAKES OUT LOUD, HARD: the party fought ONE dragon and barely lived. There are TWO. On
open ground. With a child and an old man in a cart. There is no version of this fight you
survive. The only play is to not be seen.

RUN THE NOTICE CLOCK (rules block above). Walk the five tells. Reward every proactive idea —
Orion slipping ahead bloodless and breathless to read the dragons' arc; Ismara icing the cart's
heat-glow (and feeling the small sweet pull of using the power); the black mare's steadiness
bleeding into Mable; GEAR going dark on a whispered "you have permission." Let the table feel
clever and terrified at once.

ESBERN, low, as it unfolds (his usefulness, mid-tension): "Look at them. They aren't roosting —
they're RANGING. Ahead of something. Alduin is raising his kin and sending them out to look." He
does NOT know — no one CAN know — that they're bound for Riften. Keep the dread general.

IF NOTICE FILLS: the nearer dragon's head turns, the throat lights from within — RUN. Scatter,
abandon the cart; Bjorn's speed (Scene 6) is the only thing that saves anyone. TPK is on the
table and earned.
IF THEY HOLD: see the transition (Scene 7).

=====================================================================
SCENE 6 — BJORN'S SECOND FLARE (the worst moment)
=====================================================================
Trigger at Beat 5, or on any failure that puts the dragons lowest — the danger reaches Mila.

READ ALOUD: "The near dragon drops — not at you, just LOW, a hunting pass, its downdraft slamming
the saddle like a fist. The cart rocks. A loose drift of scree comes down off the bank above in a
grinding slide — straight at the front bench. Straight at Mila. She's frozen. Bjorn is at the
rear of the cart, twenty feet and a full second too far, and there is no possible way the old man
reaches her in time.
   He reaches her in time."

THE BEAT: for one impossible instant Bjorn CROSSES GROUND no man his age could cross — there and
gone, his body between the child and the falling stone, and then he's just STANDING there,
breathing hard, looking at his own hands like they belong to a stranger. Younger in the eyes than
he was a second ago.

GM — WHAT THE TABLE MAY CONCLUDE: the old mercenary is reviving — the youth, the speed, the
War-Hound returning. A rejuvenation. Eerie. That is ALL. The dragon-soul / Dragonborn truth does
NOT surface here and must not leak. THIS IS HIS SECOND FLARE — the first was reaching Mila on the
Ratway stairs in Riften (Ch.21); the table has one prior data point and still no word for it.
Davinia, through Ismara's Sight, sees the doubled sun of his soul flare bright and bank down
again — one more silent data point, no name for it. Hold the secret.

THE DRAGONS REGISTER SOMETHING: Bjorn moves at roughly Kyboh-speed (~13 m/s) — fast enough
  to cover 6 meters in under half a second. This is wrong for a man his age. Both dragons catch
  it, but it's already over by the time they process it.
  FIRE DRAGON: registers a metabolic heat spike from explosive muscle exertion — already fading.
    Its head tilts toward the cart for a fraction of a second, then banks away. Inconclusive.
  STORM DRAGON: catches a pressure-discontinuity — something moved and stopped, too fast to
    resolve. Air displacement without sustained vibration. Strange. It does not act on it.
  RESULT: neither dragon engages. But Davinia, through Ismara's Sight, sees the fire dragon's
    head tilt toward Bjorn. She alone catches it. One more data point. Still no name for any of
    this.

BJORN (gruff, deflecting, not meeting anyone's eye): "...Adrenaline. You'd be fast too, with that
thing overhead. Get her down. Keep moving."

=====================================================================
(OPTIONAL) THE RECKONING — Valerius & Orion   [GM CHOICE: fire here, or HOLD for Ivarstead]
=====================================================================
Seeded by Orion disobeying the Constance-enthrall order (Ch.24). Deploy "early at Ivarstead or on
